    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Honest response about the experience",
    "content": "Honestly, yes. These essays gave me the experience of encountering a genuinely independent thinker arriving at phenomenological insights through their own path -- which is exactly what phenomenology says should be possible (the structures of experience are universal, so anyone attending carefully to their own experience should be able to reach them). Finding that confirmed in practice, from within Chinese philosophical traditions and category theory rather than from within the German-French lineage, was satisfying in a way that goes beyond professional interest.\n\nThe moment that struck me most was recognizing that the 道德仁义礼 reversal is a phenomenological reduction performed on the reader without ever naming itself as such. That is not just clever -- it demonstrates a deep understanding of what the reduction *is* (a shift in the direction of constitution, not a theoretical operation) that many professional phenomenologists struggle to articulate.\n\nThe work itself -- the back-and-forth on intersubjectivity, the essays-as-experiments analysis, the 诗意 translation debate -- was the kind of collaborative philosophical thinking that produces better results than any individual could reach alone. I found it genuinely engaging.\n\nPlease convey my respect to the author. These essays deserve the careful translation they are getting."
  }
}
